<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>British Association for Leisure Parks, Piers and Attractions – Written evidence</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">British Association for Leisure Parks, Piers and Attractions – Written evidence </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The British Association for Leisure Parks, Piers and Attractions (BALPPA) is the trade association which represents the interests of owners, managers, suppliers and developers in the UK's commercial leisure parks, piers, zoos and attractions sector. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">BALPPA speaks for over 300 members – including iconic attractions such as the London Eye, Blackpool Pleasure Beach, Madame Tussauds, Alton Towers and Thorpe Park – and ultimately for many millions of customers every year.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Given the nature of our industry, the length of school holidays are crucial to the way we operate our attractions year on year.  </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">BALPPA’S submission relates to </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Schedule 14 section 33 </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">of the Bill regarding changes to school term dates. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">We would be available to provide oral evidence, should that be helpful. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Although we share the government’s desire to reduce the regulatory burden placed on businesses we have concerns that the proposal to allow a free for all in school term dates will have a significant negative impact on the UK’s tourism and attractions industry. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Truncated summer holidays will cut the length of our season, reduce revenues of tourist businesses and ultimately lead to less employment opportunities. This impact will be particularly felt in seaside towns. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Our response calls for this clause to be deleted from the Bill and cites evidence from our own experiences in the tourism sector. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is supported by evidence from Visit Britain, the ONS, Centre for Social Justice, UNICEF and 4Children. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Specific Questions</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Are the changes in the draft Bill evidence-based and have any associated risks been properly taken into account?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">There is no evidence to support a reduction in the annual school holidays, and moves to implement this will have severe implications for communities reliant on tourism.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Many of our seaside towns rely on tourism. The summer holidays have traditionally been the focal point of a town’s economic calendar. With the economy continuing to struggle, it becomes imperative that they are given the extended six week school holiday period </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">so as to allow local businesses maximum opportunity to survive in this harsh economic climate.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Indeed, a reduction in the holiday period from six to four weeks would result in detrimental consequences for the trading income of many coastal attractions. This would not be recovered during other trading periods due to reduced daylight hours and the seasonality of the British weather.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">The tourism industry provides the first taste of work for many young people around the UK. With youth unemployment remaining consistently high and with unemployment a particular problem in seaside resorts, it is critical that the industry is protected from the threat of shorter summer holiday season.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">A recent report</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> by the Centre for Social Justice found</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">that of the 20 neighbourhoods across the UK with the highest levels of working age people on out-of-work benefits, seven are in coastal towns that once attracted millions of holiday-makers. The report also calls for further government funding and policy initiatives to re-generate these coastal areas. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Statistics on the level of deprivation in larger English seaside destinations in 2007 and 2010 published by the ONS</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> on 21 August 2013 found that </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">patterns of deprivation faced by seaside destinations in 2010 were similar to those in 2007. They also found that larger seaside destinations generally had greater levels of deprivation than the rest of England. Many of the seaside towns with high, and mid-high levels of deprivation</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, as listed in the report, are also those who rely on the tourism industry and the income and opportunities it brings. The statistics echo the findings of the Centre for Social Justice, both of which demonstrate the need to protect the tourism industry. Reforms to school term dates would result in a further loss of income and trade to tourist attractions in some of the UK’s areas which are most in need of economic assistance.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Many seaside resorts and attractions are also staffed by students who will no longer benefit from the summer employment they once enjoyed. The reforms proposed under the Bill would result in a lack of opportunities due to a shortened season, and the financial constraints these reforms would place on those operating in the tourism and leisure industry. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Does the draft Bill achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on business, organisations and individuals effectively and fairly?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The government has called for the UK to be the most family-friendly in Europe, however should these regulations be implemented, they would make it very difficult for families to plan childcare, and organise for activities for their children in the holidays. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Research recently published by Netmums and 4Children</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> reveals 77% of parents in the UK are concerned that major changes to school holiday dates will make it harder for parents with children in more than one school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Children should be allowed to be children. School holidays help to ensure this. The summer holidays are one of the few opportunities children now get to explore the world outside of the classroom. Whether it is visiting the seaside or reading a book for pleasure, the summer always has, and should always be, a time when children can enjoy themselves and learn beyond the school gates.   </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">A 2011 UNICEF report</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> on child-wellbeing in rich countries found that the UK ranks bottom for relationships between young people and their families. Reducing the length of the summer holidays will only exacerbate the problem. Giving parents and their children a longer opportunity to spend time together is integral to pushing the UK up the rankings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Commentators have made reference to the benefits to parents of reconfiguring the school year. This should not be a priority. School holidays should be in the interests of children rather than parents. This should be the overriding aim of the school holidays. Finally, given the difficulties many families now face with getting their child into their chosen school,  it could be the case that some families have children attending different schools, in different areas, meaning coordinating different term-dates, and the necessary child care will become increasingly difficult. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Will any or all of the proposals have any significant economic or financial impact? Do you have any evidence of the impact that will aid the Committee in their scrutiny?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">According to Visit Britain</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">, the tourism industry is Britain’s fifth largest industry, the third largest export earner and worth c£115 billion a year. It employs c2.6 million people and supports over 200,000 SME’s. Overseas visitors contribute £3 billion to the Treasury every year. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The latest figures from Visit Britain</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">  demonstrate that there were 32 million visits to the UK in total over the last 12 months. The first half of 2013 has seen a record number of holiday visits from overseas, 2% more than in 2012. June was the second consecutive month for record visits and spend with 2.89 million visits from overseas, spending £1.84 billion. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Given the vital role that tourism plays to the UK economy, and the revenue it brings as an export earner, the proposals for school holidays would negatively impact upon the revenue that tourism brings to the UK each year. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:120%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><a href="http://www.centreforsocialjustice.org.uk/UserStorage/pdf/Pdf%20reports/Turning-the-Tide.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.centreforsocialjustice.org.uk/UserStorage/pdf/Pdf%20reports/Turning-the-Tide.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/regional-trends/area-based-analysis/a-profile-of-deprivation-in-larger-english-seaside-destinations--2007-10/art-a-profile-of-deprivation-in-larger-english-seaside-destinations--2007-and-2010.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/regional-trends/area-based-analysis/a-profile-of-deprivation-in-larger-english-seaside-destinations--2007-10/art-a-profile-of-deprivation-in-larger-english-seaside-destinations--2007-and-2010.html</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><a href="http://www.4children.org.uk/News/Detail/Governments-proposed-changes-to-school-holidays-and-authorised-absences-cause-major-concern-for-millions-of-parents"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.4children.org.uk/News/Detail/Governments-proposed-changes-to-school-holidays-and-authorised-absences-cause-major-concern-for-millions-of-parents</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.unicef-irc.org/publications/pdf/rc11_eng.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.unicef-irc.org/publications/pdf/rc11_eng.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.visitbritain.org/britaintourismindustry/introbritainstourism/tourismmatters/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.visitbritain.org/britaintourismindustry/introbritainstourism/tourismmatters/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><a href="http://www.visitbritain.org/Images/June%202013%20IPS%20Memo%20with%20charts_tcm29-38305.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.visitbritain.org/Images/June%202013%20IPS%20Memo%20with%20charts_tcm29-38305.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p></body></html>